### 🎯 TL;DR - The Key Difference

```rust
// Box<dyn Trait> - dynamic dispatch, heap allocated, type erased
fn use_box_trait(obj: Box<dyn Display>) -> String {
    format!("Boxed: {}", obj)
}

// impl Trait - static dispatch, compile-time, concrete type known
fn use_impl_trait(obj: impl Display) -> String {
    format!("Impl: {}", obj)
}

// Usage
let boxed = Box::new(42) as Box<dyn Display>;  // ✨ Type erased
let result1 = use_box_trait(boxed);

let concrete = 42;  // i32 implements Display
let result2 = use_impl_trait(concrete);  // ✨ Concrete type preserved
```

**Key insight**: `Box<dyn Trait>` uses **dynamic dispatch** (runtime), `impl Trait` uses **static dispatch** (compile-time)!

---

### 🔍 Deep Dive — With EVA Energy! 💫

#### 🧱 `Box<dyn Trait>` - Dynamic Dispatch

```rust
use std::fmt::Display;

// Dynamic dispatch - can hold any type that implements Display
fn process_with_box(items: Vec<Box<dyn Display>>) {
    for item in items {
        println!("Dynamic: {}", item);
        // The actual type is erased - we only know it implements Display
    }
}

fn box_examples() {
    // Can mix different types that implement Display
    let items: Vec<Box<dyn Display>> = vec![
        Box::new(42),                    // i32
        Box::new("Hello"),               // &str
        Box::new(3.14_f64),              // f64
        Box::new(vec![1, 2, 3]),         // Vec<i32>
    ];

    process_with_box(items);
    // Each call to println! uses dynamic dispatch (virtual function call)
}
```

#### 🧱 `impl Trait` - Static Dispatch

```rust
use std::fmt::Display;

// Static dispatch - compiler generates separate function for each concrete type
fn process_with_impl<T: Display>(item: T) {
    println!("Static: {}", item);
    // The concrete type T is known at compile time
}

// Or using impl Trait syntax (same thing, different syntax)
fn process_with_impl_syntax(item: impl Display) {
    println!("Static: {}", item);
}

fn impl_examples() {
    // Each call generates a separate function instantiation
    process_with_impl(42);          // process_with_impl::<i32>
    process_with_impl("Hello");     // process_with_impl::<&str>
    process_with_impl(3.14_f64);    // process_with_impl::<f64>

    // Or using impl Trait syntax
    process_with_impl_syntax(vec![1, 2, 3]);  // process_with_impl_syntax::<Vec<i32>>
}
```

